// Content Sprint 11: Integrations and Data Flow.
window.CONTENT_SPRINT_11 = {"integration-architecture":{"summary":"Understand how the storefront, Marketplacer, Seller systems, payments, fulfilment providers and internal platforms work together, define clear system boundaries and design reliable marketplace data flows before integrations are built.","audience":["Marketplace operations","Product and ecommerce","Technology and integrations","Finance","Customer service"],"sections":{"Understand Integration Architecture":"<p>Integration architecture defines which systems participate in the marketplace, which system owns each type of information, how information moves, which identifiers connect records, what happens when a flow fails and who owns recovery.</p>\n<div class=\"structure-diagram\"><code>Seller systems\n      ↓ products, prices and stock\nMarketplacer\n      ↓\nConnected storefront\n      ↓ checkout and payment\nMarketplacer Order\n      ↓\nSeller fulfilment\n      ↓ tracking, refunds and finance</code></div>\n\n<div class=\"callout note\">\n<p>Begin with the complete business journey and system boundaries, not individual API fields or connector settings.</p>\n</div>\n","Understand the Connected Marketplace Pattern":"<p>In a connected marketplace, Marketplacer typically hosts Seller products, marketplace Orders, Seller Invoices, refund workflows and remittance records. The Operator's ecommerce platform owns customer discovery, cart, checkout, payment and customer-facing Order history. An integration layer transforms and routes data between systems.</p>\n<div class=\"data-table-wrap\"><table class=\"data-table\">\n<thead>\n<tr>\n  <th>Component</th>\n  <th>Primary responsibility</th>\n</tr>\n</thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n  <td>Marketplacer</td>\n  <td>Sellers, catalogue, Seller offers, Orders, refunds and remittance</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n  <td>Storefront</td>\n  <td>Customer experience, checkout and payment</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n  <td>Seller system</td>\n  <td>Seller product, inventory and fulfilment where connected</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n  <td>Integration layer</td>\n  <td>Transformation, routing, validation, monitoring and retry</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n  <td>Payment provider</td>\n  <td>Customer authorisation, capture and refund</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n  <td>Payout provider</td>\n  <td>Seller fund transfer</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div>\n<p>Marketplacer does not replace every existing ecommerce, ERP, CRM, payment or analytics platform.</p>\n","Define System Boundaries":"<p>Write a boundary statement for each major journey.</p>\n<ul class=\"check-list\">\n<li>Product: where Sellers create products, where Mapping and approval occur, and which system supplies the storefront</li>\n<li>Order: where the customer Order and payment are created, when Marketplacer receives it, and how Seller Invoices are split</li>\n<li>Fulfilment: where dispatch is first recorded and how tracking returns to the customer experience</li>\n<li>Refund: where the customer request, Seller decision, Marketplacer workflow and cash refund occur</li>\n<li>Finance: where commission, remittance, payout and accounting are recorded</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Prefer a specific statement such as: &quot;The storefront collects payment, then the integration submits paid Line Items to Marketplacer, which creates the Order and Seller Invoices.&quot;</p>\n","Identify the Core Systems":"<p>Document the customer storefront, Marketplacer, Seller source systems, integration layer, payment and payout providers, ERP, CRM, returns platform, fulfilment systems, analytics warehouse and any middleware.</p>\n<p>For each system, record whether it reads, writes, transforms or only displays each object. Do not combine customer-payment, Seller-payout and accounting responsibilities automatically.</p>\n","Choose Integration Patterns":"<div class=\"data-table-wrap\"><table class=\"data-table\">\n<thead>\n<tr>\n  <th>Pattern</th>\n  <th>Appropriate use</th>\n</tr>\n</thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n  <td>MConnect</td>\n  <td>Supported Seller ecommerce systems and standard product, Order and fulfilment flows</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n  <td>Operator API</td>\n  <td>Operator storefront and internal-platform integration</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n  <td>Seller API</td>\n  <td>Custom Seller integration</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n  <td>Webhooks</td>\n  <td>Event-driven notification</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n  <td>Scheduled polling</td>\n  <td>Reconciliation, reporting and recovery</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n  <td>Bulk spreadsheet</td>\n  <td>Controlled manual onboarding or maintenance</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n  <td>Middleware</td>\n  <td>Multi-system transformation and orchestration</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n  <td>Portal workflow</td>\n  <td>Low-volume or approved fallback</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div>\n<p>Different flows can use different patterns. Document how they work together rather than forcing one integration method across the marketplace.</p>\n","Map the Product and Catalogue Flow":"<div class=\"structure-diagram\"><code>Seller source\n      ↓ ingestion\nMarketplacer Seller Advert and Variants\n      ↓ Mapping and validation\nProduct Vetting\n      ↓ publication\nOperator API or connector\n      ↓\nCustomer storefront</code></div>\n\n<p>Record connection method, imported fields, source Category values, Mapping owner, update cadence, image behaviour and deletion behaviour.</p>\n<p>Separate shared product information, such as title, Brand, Category and specifications, from Seller offer information, such as price, stock, shipping and Seller identity.</p>\n","Map Pricing and Inventory":"<p>For pricing, define source price, Sale price, Promotion calculation, tax, currency, update frequency and stale-price detection.</p>\n<p>For inventory, define source location, stock buffer, oversell controls, zero-stock handling, Order reduction, update cadence and reconciliation.</p>\n<p>The Seller system may own stock while Marketplacer holds the marketplace inventory position and the storefront displays availability. All systems must agree on Variant identity.</p>\n","Map Checkout, Payment and Order Creation":"<p>A common sequence is:</p>\n<div class=\"structure-diagram\"><code>Customer checkout\n      ↓ price and stock validation\nPayment authorised or captured\n      ↓\nMarketplacer orderCreate\n      ↓\nMarketplace Order and Seller Invoices\n      ↓\nSeller fulfilment</code></div>\n\n<p>Define what occurs when payment fails, stock changes, one Line Item is invalid, Marketplacer is temporarily unavailable or the same request is submitted twice.</p>\n<p>Treat the customer Order, Marketplacer Order, Seller Invoice and Line Item as different records with linked identifiers.</p>\n","Map Seller Orders and Fulfilment":"<p>The Seller may fulfil through the Seller Portal, MConnect, Seller API or middleware.</p>\n<p>Document Seller notification, Order receipt, acknowledgement, dispatch location, Carrier, tracking, partial and split Shipment behaviour, retries and the customer-facing tracking flow.</p>\n<p>An integration is incomplete when Orders reach the Seller but fulfilment cannot return to Marketplacer and the storefront.</p>\n","Map Cancellations, Returns and Refunds":"<p>Separate customer request intake, Marketplacer Refund Request, Seller decision, return movement, Invoice Amendment, customer cash refund and Seller remittance recovery.</p>\n<div class=\"structure-diagram\"><code>Customer request\n      ↓\nCancellation or return workflow\n      ↓\nSeller decision\n      ↓\nMarketplacer financial adjustment\n      ↓\nPayment refund\n      ↓\nReconciliation</code></div>\n\n<p>Avoid unlinked refund processes. A payment-only refund can overstate Seller remittance, while a Marketplacer-only refund can leave the customer unpaid.</p>\n","Map Remittance and Payouts":"<p>Marketplacer calculates the Seller financial position. A payout provider or bank performs the actual transfer.</p>\n<p>Document remittance eligibility, delay, release method, payout schedule, payout identifiers, failed-payout handling and month-end reconciliation. A Remittance Advice and a completed bank transfer are not the same event.</p>\n","Define the Source of Truth":"<p>Assign one authoritative source to every business object and important field.</p>\n<div class=\"data-table-wrap\"><table class=\"data-table\">\n<thead>\n<tr>\n  <th>Object or field</th>\n  <th>Example source of truth</th>\n</tr>\n</thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n  <td>Seller legal details</td>\n  <td>Marketplacer or approved CRM</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n  <td>Product description</td>\n  <td>Seller source, CPD or Marketplacer</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n  <td>Marketplace Category</td>\n  <td>Marketplacer</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n  <td>Price and stock</td>\n  <td>Approved Seller or pricing system</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n  <td>Payment status</td>\n  <td>Payment provider</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n  <td>Marketplace Order</td>\n  <td>Marketplacer</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n  <td>Seller Shipment</td>\n  <td>Seller system or Marketplacer</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n  <td>Customer cash refund</td>\n  <td>Payment provider</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n  <td>Remittance</td>\n  <td>Marketplacer</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n  <td>Seller bank payment</td>\n  <td>Payout provider</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div>\n<p>Avoid uncontrolled dual ownership.</p>\n","Preserve Identifiers Across Systems":"<p>Retain Marketplacer GraphQL and Legacy IDs where used, source Product and Variant IDs, storefront IDs, Marketplacer Order and Invoice IDs, Line Item IDs, payment references, Shipment IDs, Refund Request IDs and payout references.</p>\n<p>Create a correlation standard that links the customer transaction, payment, Marketplacer Order and Seller-system records. Do not use customer name or email as the primary key.</p>\n","Design for Asynchronous Processing":"<p>Assume that product imports, Product Vetting, publication, Webhooks, search indexing, payment callbacks, fulfilment and remittance can be asynchronous.</p>\n<p>Document expected timing and alert thresholds for every flow. A delay becomes an exception only after it exceeds the approved operating expectation.</p>\n<p>Before manually duplicating an apparently delayed action, inspect the source, integration, Marketplacer, destination and retry state.</p>\n","Design Retries and Duplicate Prevention":"<p>Retry temporary network, rate-limit and service-availability failures. Correct invalid payloads, credentials, scopes and business-state errors before another attempt.</p>\n<p>For Orders, refunds and payments, store stable External IDs, original request, response, retry count, final Marketplacer ID and processing state. Search for the expected record before retrying an uncertain mutation.</p>\n<p>Webhook consumers must also be idempotent even when Marketplacer deduplication is enabled.</p>\n","Secure the Integration":"<p>Use separate credentials per integration and environment, least-privilege scopes, approved secrets storage, HTTPS and credential rotation.</p>\n<p>For Webhooks, validate HMAC or approved authentication headers, protect against replay, log validation failures and acknowledge quickly before asynchronous processing.</p>\n<p>Never place API keys or secrets in source control, spreadsheets, tickets or screenshots.</p>\n","Monitor and Reconcile Data Flows":"<p>Monitoring should prove whether the source created the event, the integration received and transformed it, the destination accepted it and the business outcome completed.</p>\n<p>Monitor products not imported, stale prices and stock, missing Orders, Seller Invoices not received, missing Shipments, failed Webhooks, refund mismatches and unmatched remittances.</p>\n<p>Webhooks and successful API responses show communication. Reconciliation confirms that the systems still agree.</p>\n","Separate Sandbox and Production":"<p>Use separate API keys, endpoints, Webhook secrets, payment credentials, Seller connections, data stores and monitoring for Sandbox and Production.</p>\n<p>Before a Sandbox refresh, record Webhook and MConnect configuration. After refresh, recreate integrations where required and run smoke tests. A Production Webhook must never send live data to a Sandbox endpoint.</p>\n","Assign Ownership and Support Responsibilities":"<p>Every flow needs a business owner, technical owner, operational monitor, escalation path and recovery procedure.</p>\n<div class=\"data-table-wrap\"><table class=\"data-table\">\n<thead>\n<tr>\n  <th>Flow</th>\n  <th>Business owner</th>\n  <th>Technical owner</th>\n  <th>Monitor</th>\n</tr>\n</thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n  <td>Product import</td>\n  <td>Catalogue</td>\n  <td>Integration team</td>\n  <td>Marketplace Operations</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n  <td>Orders</td>\n  <td>Ecommerce</td>\n  <td>Integration team</td>\n  <td>Customer service</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n  <td>Fulfilment</td>\n  <td>Seller management</td>\n  <td>Seller or integration team</td>\n  <td>Marketplace Operations</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n  <td>Refunds</td>\n  <td>Customer service</td>\n  <td>Payments and integration teams</td>\n  <td>Refund Operations</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n  <td>Remittance</td>\n  <td>Finance</td>\n  <td>Payout team</td>\n  <td>Finance</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div>\n<p>Escalate to Marketplacer Support when evidence points to unexpected Marketplacer behaviour, and include environment, IDs, timestamps, request and response evidence and impact.</p>\n","Document the Architecture":"<p>Maintain a system context diagram, separate data-flow diagrams for products, stock, Orders, fulfilment, refunds and remittance, an integration register, a field-ownership matrix and operational runbooks.</p>\n<p>Each integration register entry should include source, destination, method, trigger, frequency, authentication, identifiers, owner, monitor, failure queue and recovery process.</p>\n","Test the Architecture End to End":"<p>Test complete product, Order, fulfilment, refund and Finance journeys, including failure cases such as payment success with Order failure, duplicate Order submission, stale stock, unavailable Seller systems, failed Webhooks and refunds completed in only one system.</p>\n<p>Architecture is ready when every flow has a source and destination, every object has an authority, retries are duplicate-safe, failures alert an owner, Finance can reconcile and customer service can locate the complete transaction.</p>\n","Operator Readiness Checklist":"<ul class=\"check-list\">\n<li>system boundaries and participating platforms are documented</li>\n<li>product, price, stock, Order, fulfilment, refund and remittance flows are mapped</li>\n<li>every object and field has a source of truth</li>\n<li>stable identifiers are retained across systems</li>\n<li>asynchronous timing and alert thresholds are documented</li>\n<li>retries are bounded and duplicate-safe</li>\n<li>API keys and Webhooks follow least privilege and approved security controls</li>\n<li>Sandbox and Production are separated</li>\n<li>operational monitoring and reconciliation are assigned</li>\n<li>architecture diagrams, registers and runbooks are current</li>\n<li>end-to-end and failure-recovery testing has passed</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>Related Marketplacer articles</h3>\n<ul class=\"check-list\">\n<li><a href=\"https://api.marketplacer.com/docs/operator-api/overview/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Operator API overview</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"https://api.marketplacer.com/docs/operator-api/examples/orders/howto_order/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Creating Orders</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"https://dev.marketplacer.com/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Marketplacer Developer Portal</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"https://api.marketplacer.com/docs/webhooks/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Webhooks overview</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"https://api.marketplacer.com/docs/webhooks/webhookretries/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Webhook retry policy</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"https://api.marketplacer.com/docs/webhooks/deduplication/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Webhook deduplication</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"https://api.marketplacer.com/docs/webhooks/securingwebhooks/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Securing Webhooks</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"https://api.marketplacer.com/docs/webhooks/eventmatrix/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Webhook Event Matrix</a></li>\n</ul>\n"},"related":[["apis","APIs"],["webhooks","Webhooks"],["source-of-truth-planning","Source-of-Truth Planning"],["integration-troubleshooting","Integration Troubleshooting"],["mconnect","MConnect"]]},"apis":{"summary":"Use Marketplacer Operator and Seller GraphQL APIs securely, preserve identifiers, design efficient and duplicate-safe requests, monitor integrations and manage changes throughout the marketplace lifecycle.","audience":["Technology and integrations","Product and ecommerce","Marketplace operations","Seller onboarding","Finance"],"sections":{"Understand Marketplacer APIs":"<p>Marketplacer provides GraphQL APIs that external systems can use for products, Sellers, taxonomy, Orders, Shipments, refunds, Promotions, Golden Records and remittance. Webhooks complement the APIs by announcing supported events.</p>\n<div class=\"structure-diagram\"><code>External system\n      ↓ GraphQL request\nMarketplacer API\n      ↓ query or mutation\nGraphQL response\n      ↓\nExternal system records the result</code></div>\n\n<p>The API provides technical capability. Every flow still needs a business process, owner, monitoring and recovery plan.</p>\n","Choose the Operator API or Seller API":"<div class=\"data-table-wrap\"><table class=\"data-table\">\n<thead>\n<tr>\n  <th>API</th>\n  <th>Typical user</th>\n  <th>Scope</th>\n</tr>\n</thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n  <td>Operator API</td>\n  <td>Operator storefront, middleware and internal systems</td>\n  <td>Marketplace-wide products, Orders, taxonomy, Sellers, refunds and remittance according to key scopes</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n  <td>Seller API</td>\n  <td>One Seller or its integration partner</td>\n  <td>That Seller's products, Invoices, Shipments and supported workflows</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div>\n<p>Use the Operator API for the Operator storefront and marketplace-wide operations. Use the Seller API for a Seller's own automation. Do not give a Seller an Operator key as a shortcut.</p>\n","Avoid the Legacy Seller API":"<p>New Seller integrations should use the current GraphQL Seller API. The older REST Seller API is considered legacy and does not receive the same future development.</p>\n<p>For an existing REST integration, review the feature matrix, plan the GraphQL replacement, test it and retire the old dependency. Do not begin a new implementation with a legacy endpoint simply because an older example uses it.</p>\n","Understand GraphQL":"<p>A <strong>query</strong> retrieves information. A <strong>mutation</strong> creates, updates or progresses data. Both use the marketplace <code>/graphql</code> endpoint with JSON requests.</p>\n<p>Request only the fields required by the business process, identifiers needed for later actions, timestamps and statuses. Avoid deeply nested exploratory queries in Production.</p>\n<p>Sanitise untrusted HTML before rendering API content in a storefront.</p>\n","Define the API Use Case":"<p>Record the business process, initiating system, API perspective, objects, trigger, timing, identifiers, failure process and owners before generating credentials.</p>\n<p>For an Order integration, document the full sequence from payment through <code>orderCreate</code>, response validation, Marketplacer ID storage, Seller Invoice confirmation and exception handling. Separate read-only reporting flows from write integrations.</p>\n","Create and Manage API Keys":"<p>Operator keys are created under <strong>Configuration &gt; Marketplacer API Keys</strong>. Seller keys are created in the Seller Portal under <strong>Extensions &gt; API Access</strong> after the Operator enables access.</p>\n<p>Use meaningful descriptions that identify integration, environment, owner and purpose. Copy the key into an approved vault immediately because the complete value cannot be retrieved again.</p>\n<p>Maintain a key register with perspective, environment, owner, scopes, creation and rotation dates, vault reference and status. Do not store the secret in an ordinary spreadsheet.</p>\n","Apply API Key Scopes":"<p>Scopes combine a resource and access level. Read allows retrieval, write includes read plus create or update, and manage includes destructive or irreversible actions.</p>\n<p>Use least privilege and separate keys for catalogue, Orders, Finance and administration. A missing scope can return a <code>MISSING_SCOPE</code> GraphQL error. Existing scopes cannot be edited, so create a replacement key, deploy it, then revoke the old key.</p>\n<p>Review legacy unscoped keys and migrate them to explicit scopes.</p>\n","Authenticate API Requests":"<p>Use one API-key method:</p>\n<pre><code class=\"language-text\">Authorization: Bearer &lt;API_KEY&gt;\n</code></pre>\n<p>or:</p>\n<pre><code class=\"language-text\">marketplacer-api-key: &lt;API_KEY&gt;\n</code></pre>\n<p>Some non-Production environments also require Basic Authentication. In that case, use Basic Authentication for the environment and the Marketplacer API key in its own header.</p>\n<p>Never expose API keys in browser JavaScript, mobile code, source control, tickets, screenshots or customer-facing errors.</p>\n","Use the API Documentation and Collections":"<p>Use Getting Started guides for connection, playbooks for end-to-end patterns, how-to guides for workflows, generated reference documentation for schema details, Voyager for visual exploration, Postman or Insomnia collections for examples and the changelog for changes.</p>\n<p>Collections are examples, not a complete schema. Use variables rather than embedding Production values in reusable queries.</p>\n","Understand Queries and Mutations":"<p>Always request the created or updated record ID, mutation status and validation errors. HTTP <code>200</code> does not prove a mutation succeeded because GraphQL can return operation errors inside the response body.</p>\n<p>Common operations include product upsert, <code>orderCreate</code>, Shipment creation, Refund Request mutations, External ID upsert and metadata updates. Confirm the current schema and required scopes before implementation.</p>\n","Work with Marketplacer IDs":"<p>Treat GraphQL IDs as opaque Marketplacer identifiers. Use them when linking objects or performing later GraphQL actions. Legacy IDs can help Portal and Support investigation. External IDs correlate the same record in another system.</p>\n<p>Preserve relevant Product, Variant, Order, Invoice, Line Item, Shipment, refund, payment and payout identifiers. Do not build business logic by decoding a GraphQL ID.</p>\n","Use External IDs, Metadata and Custom Fields":"<p>Use External IDs for durable third-party identifiers and reconciliation. Use metadata for integration context such as source channel, routing code or migration batch. Use approved custom fields for structured marketplace information supported by the object model.</p>\n<div class=\"data-table-wrap\"><table class=\"data-table\">\n<thead>\n<tr>\n  <th>Requirement</th>\n  <th>Use</th>\n</tr>\n</thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n  <td>Third-party record identifier</td>\n  <td>External ID</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n  <td>Integration-only context</td>\n  <td>Metadata</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n  <td>Marketplace-defined structured attribute</td>\n  <td>Custom field</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n  <td>Existing platform behaviour</td>\n  <td>Native field</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div>\n<p>Do not replace a native field with metadata merely because it is easier for the integration.</p>\n","Retrieve Marketplace Products":"<p>Marketplacer uses <strong>Advert</strong> as the API term for Product. Customer availability commonly depends on <code>published</code>, <code>displayable</code> and <code>online</code> being true.</p>\n<p>Choose the query according to whether the integration needs customer-ready products, updates, unpublished records or deletion detection. Define how the storefront deactivates products after soft deletion or missed events.</p>\n","Create Marketplace Orders":"<p>In the connected pattern, the storefront usually completes payment, then calls <code>orderCreate</code> so Marketplacer creates the Order and Seller Invoices.</p>\n<div class=\"structure-diagram\"><code>Customer checkout and payment\n      ↓\norderCreate\n      ↓\nMarketplacer Order\n      ↓\nSeller A Invoice + Seller B Invoice\n      ↓\nSeller fulfilment</code></div>\n\n<p>Prefer Line Item input for standard Orders so Marketplacer can split Seller Invoices. Confirm customer details, Variant IDs, quantity, item cost, tax, postage, Promotion adjustments, External IDs and notification behaviour.</p>\n<p>Protect <code>orderCreate</code> from duplicate submission.</p>\n","Support Seller Orders and Fulfilment":"<p>A Seller API integration can retrieve the Seller's Invoices and create Shipments.</p>\n<p>Retain Invoice and Line Item IDs, dispatched quantities, Carrier, tracking, source fulfilment ID and resulting Shipment ID. Test full, partial and multiple Shipments. Do not mark an entire Invoice fulfilled when only part of its quantity was dispatched.</p>\n","Support Refunds and Remittance":"<p>API refund workflows must distinguish the Marketplacer Refund Request, Seller action, Invoice Amendment, customer cash refund and Seller remittance adjustment.</p>\n<p>A successful Marketplacer mutation does not prove the payment provider returned money unless that step is integrated and confirmed.</p>\n<p>Use remittance data for payout integration and Finance reconciliation. Do not treat Seller Invoice gross value as the amount payable without commission, fees, tax and adjustments.</p>\n","Paginate Result Sets":"<p>Marketplacer GraphQL APIs use cursor-based pagination with <code>first</code>, <code>after</code>, <code>pageInfo.hasNextPage</code> and <code>pageInfo.endCursor</code>.</p>\n<div class=\"structure-diagram\"><code>Request page\n      ↓\nRead hasNextPage and endCursor\n      ↓\nPass cursor into after\n      ↓\nRepeat until complete</code></div>\n\n<p>Use a controlled page size and follow the specific query documentation. Store extraction position so long-running jobs can restart safely.</p>\n","Design Efficient Queries":"<p>Select only required fields, use variables, filter at the API, cache stable data and use update timestamps or object state for incremental work where supported.</p>\n<p>Avoid retrieving large nested relationships or full marketplaces only to discard most records locally. Split complex requirements into controlled queries before reaching query-depth or performance limits.</p>\n","Handle GraphQL and HTTP Errors":"<p>Inspect both transport and GraphQL results.</p>\n<ul class=\"check-list\">\n<li>Transport: timeout, authentication failure, <code>429</code>, <code>503</code> or gateway error</li>\n<li>GraphQL: top-level <code>errors</code>, <code>extensions.code</code>, error path, mutation-specific errors and partial data</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Classify failures as transient, authentication, permission, validation, business state, duplicate or unexpected platform behaviour. A partial GraphQL response can contain both usable data and failed fields.</p>\n","Manage Rate Limits":"<p>Treat current rate limits as changeable platform controls. Respond to <code>429</code> or <code>503</code>, respect <code>retry-after</code>, reduce concurrency, paginate, cache and avoid repeated identical queries.</p>\n<p>Use exponential backoff and jitter for temporary limits. Do not hardcode the assumption that today's request thresholds will never change.</p>\n","Design Retries":"<p>Retry temporary network, timeout, <code>429</code> and <code>5xx</code> conditions. Correct malformed payloads, invalid IDs, credentials, scopes and business validation before retrying.</p>\n<p>A safe strategy respects <code>retry-after</code>, uses exponential backoff and jitter, sets a maximum attempt count, tracks retry context, moves exhausted work to an exception queue and alerts an owner.</p>\n","Prevent Duplicate Mutations":"<p>Read queries are generally safe to repeat. Mutations such as Order, Shipment or refund creation can create duplicate business records.</p>\n<p>Use stable External IDs, database uniqueness constraints, one active processing owner, message deduplication and transaction state. After a timeout, search for the expected record before retrying.</p>\n","Use HMAC for Sensitive Mutations":"<p>Where the implementation uses Marketplacer mutation HMAC support, validate request integrity with the associated secret. HMAC complements TLS, scopes, secret storage, request validation and duplicate prevention.</p>\n<p>Rotate the HMAC secret when the related API key or security boundary changes.</p>\n","Secure and Rotate API Keys":"<p>Store credentials in an approved secrets manager, restrict key creation and document planned and emergency rotation.</p>\n<p>Rotation sequence: create a replacement key, right-size scopes, test it, deploy to all consumers, monitor and revoke the old key. Rotate immediately after suspected exposure or unauthorised use.</p>\n","Combine APIs with Webhooks":"<p>Use Webhooks for timely notification and APIs for current state, additional detail, recovery and reconciliation.</p>\n<div class=\"structure-diagram\"><code>Webhook announces change\n      ↓\nConsumer stores event\n      ↓\nAPI retrieves authoritative state\n      ↓\nDestination updates\n      ↓\nScheduled reconciliation detects misses</code></div>\n\n","Monitor and Reconcile API Flows":"<p>Log environment, timestamp, correlation ID, operation name, object type, External ID, Marketplacer ID, HTTP status, GraphQL errors, attempt count, duration and outcome. Do not log secrets or unnecessary personal data.</p>\n<p>Monitor success rate, latency, rate limits, retry volume, queue age, mutation failures, duplicates and unmatched transactions. Schedule reconciliation for products, stock, Orders, Shipments, refunds and remittance.</p>\n","Manage API Changes and Deprecations":"<p>Assign an owner to monitor the Marketplacer API changelog, schema changes and deprecation notices. Test replacements in Sandbox, update integrations before removal and confirm deprecated fields are no longer requested.</p>\n<p>Do not leave static onboarding queries unreviewed indefinitely. Use schema validation and automated tests.</p>\n","Separate Sandbox and Production":"<p>Separate endpoint, API key, Basic Authentication, HMAC, External ID namespace, Webhook endpoint, payment credentials, queues and alerts by environment.</p>\n<p>Never automatically fall back between environments. After a Sandbox refresh, revalidate credentials, Webhooks, object IDs and smoke tests.</p>\n","Troubleshoot API Issues":"<h3>Authentication failure</h3>\n<p>Check endpoint, key, header, Basic Authentication, revocation and deployment.</p>\n<h3>Missing scope</h3>\n<p>Inspect <code>extensions.code</code> and create a correctly scoped replacement key.</p>\n<h3>HTTP 200 but nothing changed</h3>\n<p>Inspect top-level GraphQL errors, mutation errors, status, validation and returned object.</p>\n<h3>Duplicate Order</h3>\n<p>Review External ID, timeout, retry history, queue duplication and existing Marketplacer records.</p>\n<h3>Product not visible</h3>\n<p>Check <code>published</code>, <code>displayable</code>, <code>online</code>, Seller status, stock, Product Vetting and storefront processing.</p>\n","Test APIs End to End":"<p>Test Operator and Seller authentication, required and missing scopes, variables, pagination, GraphQL errors, Product retrieval, deletion handling, one-Seller and multi-Seller Orders, External IDs, duplicate retries, Seller fulfilment, refund and remittance reconciliation, rate limits, retry exhaustion, key rotation and environment isolation.</p>\n","Operator Readiness Checklist":"<ul class=\"check-list\">\n<li>business use case, API perspective and system boundaries are documented</li>\n<li>no new dependency uses the Legacy Seller API</li>\n<li>keys have meaningful descriptions, least-privilege scopes and vault storage</li>\n<li>Sandbox and Production credentials are separate</li>\n<li>identifiers and External IDs support reconciliation</li>\n<li>queries are efficient and paginated</li>\n<li>GraphQL errors are inspected even after HTTP 200</li>\n<li>mutations are duplicate-safe</li>\n<li>retry, exception and monitoring processes are owned</li>\n<li>Order, fulfilment, refund and remittance journeys reconcile end to end</li>\n<li>key rotation, API changes and deprecations are governed</li>\n<li>complete failure and recovery testing has passed</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>Related Marketplacer articles</h3>\n<ul class=\"check-list\">\n<li><a href=\"https://api.marketplacer.com/docs/operator-api/overview/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Operator API overview</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"https://api.marketplacer.com/docs/operator-api/gettingstarted/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Operator API Getting Started</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"https://api.marketplacer.com/docs/seller-api/overview/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Seller API overview</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"https://api.marketplacer.com/docs/seller-api/getting_started/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Seller API Getting Started</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"https://api.marketplacer.com/playbooks/general/api_key_scopes/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">API key scopes</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"https://api.marketplacer.com/playbooks/general/api_key_rotation/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">API key rotation</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"https://api.marketplacer.com/docs/operator-api/examples/orders/howto_order/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Creating Orders</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"https://api.marketplacer.com/docs/operator-api/examples/product/howto_queryadverts/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Querying Products</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"https://api.marketplacer.com/docs/operator-api/examples/utility/howto_paginate/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Pagination</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"https://api.marketplacer.com/docs/operator-api/examples/utility/howto_ids/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">ID types</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"https://api.marketplacer.com/playbooks/general/retrying/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Retrying requests</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"https://api.marketplacer.com/docs/changes/deprecation_process/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">API deprecation process</a></li>\n</ul>\n"},"related":[["integration-architecture","Integration Architecture"],["webhooks","Webhooks"],["source-of-truth-planning","Source-of-Truth Planning"],["integration-troubleshooting","Integration Troubleshooting"],["mconnect","MConnect"]]},"webhooks":{"summary":"Configure and operate Marketplacer Webhooks for event-driven integrations, secure endpoints, control payloads and volume, process events safely and reconcile missed or out-of-order updates.","audience":["Technology and integrations","Marketplace operations","Ecommerce","Catalogue teams","Finance"],"sections":{"Understand Marketplacer Webhooks":"<p>A Webhook lets Marketplacer notify another system when a supported marketplace event occurs. Marketplacer sends an HTTP POST with JSON to the registered endpoint.</p>\n<div class=\"structure-diagram\"><code>Marketplacer object changes\n      ↓\nWebhook event generated\n      ↓\nPOST to HTTPS endpoint\n      ↓\nEndpoint acknowledges\n      ↓\nEvent processed and destination updated</code></div>\n\n<p>A Webhook notification does not prove the destination completed the business action. The integration still needs validation, duplicate handling, monitoring, recovery and reconciliation.</p>\n","Choose Webhooks or API Polling":"<p>Use Webhooks when updates should be announced soon after an event and repeated polling would be wasteful. Use API queries when retrieving current state, historical data, scheduled reports or recovery after missed events.</p>\n<p>Recommended pattern: Webhook for timeliness, API for authoritative state and scheduled reconciliation for completeness.</p>\n","Define the Webhook Use Case":"<p>Record the business event, Marketplacer object, required event names, receiving system, payload, action, duplicate key, latency target, failure process, reconciliation and owners.</p>\n<p>Separate acceptance from action. A robust Invoice consumer verifies authenticity, checks idempotency, stores the event, returns <code>2xx</code>, retrieves or validates the Invoice, checks for an existing Seller Order and then creates or updates the destination.</p>\n","Understand Operator and Seller Webhooks":"<p>Operator Webhooks can cover marketplace-level objects such as Adverts, Variants, Invoices, Shipments, refunds, Sellers, Promotions, taxonomy, Shipping Rules and Remittance Advices. Seller Webhooks expose a narrower Seller-relevant set.</p>\n<p>Use Operator Webhooks for Operator-owned systems and cross-Seller data. Use Seller Webhooks when one Seller consumes only its permitted events.</p>\n","Select the Webhook Object":"<p>Choose the object that most directly represents the change.</p>\n<div class=\"data-table-wrap\"><table class=\"data-table\">\n<thead>\n<tr>\n  <th>Object</th>\n  <th>Typical use</th>\n</tr>\n</thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n  <td>Advert</td>\n  <td>Product content and publication</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n  <td>Variant</td>\n  <td>Stock, price and Variant changes</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n  <td>Invoice</td>\n  <td>Seller Order creation and status</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n  <td>Shipment</td>\n  <td>Tracking and fulfilment</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n  <td>Refund Request</td>\n  <td>Cancellation and return workflow</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n  <td>Seller</td>\n  <td>Seller account change</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n  <td>Promotion</td>\n  <td>Campaign configuration</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n  <td>Remittance Advice</td>\n  <td>Finance and payout integration</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n  <td>Category</td>\n  <td>Taxonomy synchronisation</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div>\n<p>For high-frequency inventory, a small Variant Webhook is usually better than a large Advert payload.</p>\n","Select the Event":"<p>A Webhook can receive all supported events for an object or filter to one Event Name such as <code>create</code>, <code>update</code> or <code>destroy</code>.</p>\n<p>Filter when the consumer needs one transition, such as Invoice create. Leave unfiltered when the complete lifecycle matters, such as Refund Requests. The consumer must still inspect the event name.</p>\n","Understand Related and Cascading Events":"<p>One business action can generate events for related objects. Variant changes can cause Variant and Advert updates. Order creation can reduce stock and generate Product events. Shipment creation can generate Shipment and Invoice events. Refund activity can update the parent Invoice.</p>\n<p>Promotion changes generate Promotion events independently and do not automatically create Advert events merely because products are targeted.</p>\n<p>Design consumers to avoid processing the same business action twice through related streams.</p>\n","Access Webhook Management":"<p>Operators use <strong>Configuration &gt; Webhooks</strong>. Sellers use <strong>Extensions &gt; Webhooks</strong>. Authorised users can create, edit, enable, disable and inspect events and responses.</p>\n<p>Apply least privilege. Users investigating delivery do not automatically need permission to modify Production definitions.</p>\n","Configure a Webhook":"<p>Review Enabled, Allow Skip, object Type, Event Name, URL, Maximum retries, Maximum concurrent deliveries, custom headers, HMAC and GraphQL payload.</p>\n<p>New Webhooks are not necessarily enabled automatically. Confirm enabled state after saving. Choose concurrency that the receiving service can handle safely.</p>\n","Configure Webhooks through the API":"<p>The Operator GraphQL API can create, update and query Webhooks, Events and Responses. This is useful for recreating approved Sandbox Webhooks after a refresh or auditing configuration against a register.</p>\n<p>Keep environment-specific endpoints and secrets separate even when the rest of the definition is reusable.</p>\n","Design the Webhook Payload":"<p>Use a small default payload or a tailored GraphQL payload. A custom query must accept <code>$id</code> as <code>ID!</code>, call <code>node(id: $id)</code> and use an inline fragment for the selected object.</p>\n<p>Include object ID, Legacy or External IDs, status, update timestamp and routing fields required for immediate processing. Avoid unnecessary customer data, large relationships and fast-changing fields that do not serve the consumer.</p>\n<p>For critical flows, a small Webhook can announce the object and an API query can retrieve current authoritative state.</p>\n","Understand Webhook Headers":"<p>Useful Marketplacer headers include Idempotency-Key, Marketplacer-Hmac-256, Marketplacer-Sequence, Marketplacer-Vertical, traceparent, tracestate and Content-Type.</p>\n<p>Store Idempotency Key, Sequence, originating instance, trace context and arrival time. Header names are case-insensitive, while values can be case-sensitive.</p>\n","Secure the Webhook Endpoint":"<p>Use HTTPS and validate either an approved custom authentication header or Operator Webhook HMAC. HMAC is calculated from the exact raw request body and shared secret.</p>\n<p>Do not rely solely on Marketplacer source-IP allowlisting because outbound IP addresses can change. Separate Sandbox and Production secrets, store them in a vault, use constant-time signature comparison and never log secrets.</p>\n","Build the Receiving Service":"<p>The endpoint should read the raw body, verify authentication, validate content type, read the Idempotency Key, store the event durably, return <code>2xx</code> quickly and process asynchronously.</p>\n<p>Do not hold the HTTP request open while updating large indexes or calling several downstream platforms. The receiving application should validate environment, object type, event name, identifiers and whether the action already completed.</p>\n","Acknowledge Delivery Correctly":"<p>Marketplacer treats HTTP <code>2xx</code> as successful delivery. Return <code>2xx</code> after the event is authenticated and durably accepted, not necessarily after all downstream work completes.</p>\n<div class=\"data-table-wrap\"><table class=\"data-table\">\n<thead>\n<tr>\n  <th>Response</th>\n  <th>Delivery effect</th>\n</tr>\n</thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n  <td><code>2xx</code></td>\n  <td>Sent</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n  <td><code>429</code></td>\n  <td>Retriable and can reduce concurrency</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n  <td><code>5xx</code></td>\n  <td>Retriable</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n  <td>Most other <code>4xx</code></td>\n  <td>Non-retriable; event can fail and disable the Webhook</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div>\n<p>Do not return <code>400</code> for a temporary internal outage.</p>\n","Process Events Idempotently":"<p>Use the Idempotency Key to identify repeated delivery of the same Marketplacer event. Store processing state, attempts, outcome and error.</p>\n<p>The business action also needs a stable uniqueness rule. Before creating a Seller-system Order, check whether that Marketplacer Invoice already has an external Order ID.</p>\n","Handle Event Ordering":"<p>Events can arrive out of generation order. Use Marketplacer-Sequence and object timestamps rather than arrival time alone.</p>\n<p>For product and inventory, querying current state can make strict event replay unnecessary. For workflows where transitions matter, store and sequence events so an older update cannot overwrite a newer one.</p>\n","Configure Deduplication":"<p>Marketplacer applies standard short-window deduplication. <strong>Allow Skip</strong> adds payload-based skipping when the event type and payload are identical to the previous event for the same object.</p>\n<p>Use it to reduce unchanged parent Advert events. Do not use it when every transition must be audited or the consumer needs every inventory movement.</p>\n<p>Payload design affects deduplication. Including fast-changing fields in an Advert payload can make every event appear unique.</p>\n","Plan for High Event Volume":"<p>Product and inventory streams can produce large backlogs. Return <code>2xx</code> quickly, queue internally, scale the receiver, keep payloads small, use appropriate concurrency and separate high-volume Variant inventory from lower-volume product content.</p>\n<p>For high-volume Webhooks, delivered event evidence can be retained for less time. Maintain durable receiver-side logs.</p>\n","Understand the Retry Policy":"<p>Marketplacer retries network errors, timeouts, <code>5xx</code> and <code>429</code>. Most other <code>4xx</code> responses and excessive redirects are non-retriable.</p>\n<p>Retries use exponential backoff, bounded by configured retry count and time. Configuration changes, such as a corrected URL, apply to later attempts.</p>\n<p>Marketplacer delivery retries and the consumer's internal processing retries are separate layers.</p>\n","Understand Webhook Event Statuses":"<div class=\"data-table-wrap\"><table class=\"data-table\">\n<thead>\n<tr>\n  <th>Status</th>\n  <th>Meaning</th>\n</tr>\n</thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n  <td>Unsent</td>\n  <td>Generated, not yet attempted</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n  <td>Sent</td>\n  <td>Endpoint returned <code>2xx</code></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n  <td>Rejected</td>\n  <td>Retry cycle is active</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n  <td>Failed</td>\n  <td>Delivery ended unsuccessfully</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n  <td>Cancelled</td>\n  <td>Retry cycle stopped manually</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n  <td>Skipped</td>\n  <td>Allow Skip prevented delivery</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div>\n<p>Sent proves only endpoint acceptance, not completed downstream processing.</p>\n","Cancel and Requeue Events":"<p>Authorised users can intervene in supported statuses through Webhook Management. Before requeueing, check whether a previous attempt already completed the destination action, review the Idempotency Key, confirm the event is still relevant and correct the endpoint.</p>\n<p>Requeue once and monitor the new response and business reconciliation.</p>\n","Monitor Webhook Events and Responses":"<p>Inspect triggering object, event name, Idempotency Key, payload, status, generation time and delivery responses.</p>\n<p>Monitor disabled Webhooks, Rejected and Failed events, growing backlog, repeated <code>429</code>, consumer queue depth, HMAC failures, processing latency and destination success.</p>\n<p>Marketplacer event evidence has limited retention, so the receiver must retain its own durable logs.</p>\n","Handle Payload Errors":"<p>Distinguish a normal payload containing <code>data</code> from a payload containing GraphQL <code>errors</code>. Do not assume every delivered event contains usable business data.</p>\n<p>Changing an older Webhook away from legacy payload format can alter the body shape. Treat that as an integration release with compatibility testing.</p>\n","Combine Webhooks with API Reconciliation":"<p>Schedule API reconciliation for critical Products, Orders, Shipments, refunds and Remittance Advices. Webhooks provide timeliness; API comparison confirms complete current state after missed events, prolonged outages or consumer failures.</p>\n","Separate Sandbox and Production":"<p>Create separate URL, HMAC secret, authentication header, queue, event store, API key and alerts per environment.</p>\n<p>Validate the originating Marketplacer instance before processing. Reject cross-environment delivery. After a Sandbox refresh, recreate Webhooks, verify enabled state and run event and HMAC smoke tests.</p>\n","Apply Webhook Change Control":"<p>Treat URL, object, event filter, payload, HMAC, headers, Allow Skip, concurrency, retries, enabled state and legacy format as controlled changes.</p>\n<p>Record the current configuration, test in Sandbox, validate compatibility and ordering, deploy consumer and Webhook changes in the correct sequence and monitor reconciliation after Production release.</p>\n","Troubleshoot Webhook Issues":"<h3>No event</h3>\n<p>Check enabled state, object, Event Name, Event Matrix and retention.</p>\n<h3>Rejected or Failed</h3>\n<p>Inspect timeout, <code>429</code>, <code>5xx</code>, authentication, DNS, TLS and receiver capacity.</p>\n<h3>Sent but destination unchanged</h3>\n<p>Inspect the receiver queue, processing logs, dead-letter queue, destination response and duplicate guard.</p>\n<h3>Duplicate events</h3>\n<p>Compare Idempotency Key and determine whether events are retries or different related-object events.</p>\n<h3>Out of order</h3>\n<p>Use Marketplacer Sequence, object timestamp and current API state.</p>\n","Test Webhooks End to End":"<p>Test Operator and Seller definitions, enabled state, default and custom payloads, HMAC, Advert and Variant events, Order and Shipment events, refund transitions, related cascading events, <code>200</code>, <code>429</code>, <code>500</code>, <code>400</code>, timeout, duplicate delivery, out-of-order arrival, high volume, requeue, API reconciliation and environment isolation.</p>\n","Operator Readiness Checklist":"<ul class=\"check-list\">\n<li>each Webhook has a documented business purpose and owner</li>\n<li>Operator or Seller level, object and Event Name are intentional</li>\n<li>Event Matrix and related events are understood</li>\n<li>endpoint is HTTPS and validates HMAC or approved authentication</li>\n<li>events are stored durably and acknowledged quickly</li>\n<li>Idempotency Key and Marketplacer Sequence are retained</li>\n<li>destination actions are duplicate-safe</li>\n<li>payload and concurrency match receiver capacity</li>\n<li>retry and <code>4xx</code> consequences are understood</li>\n<li>event and consumer monitoring are separate</li>\n<li>API reconciliation is scheduled for critical objects</li>\n<li>Sandbox and Production definitions and secrets are separated</li>\n<li>changes and Sandbox refresh recovery follow documented processes</li>\n<li>complete delivery, failure and recovery testing has passed</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>Related Marketplacer articles</h3>\n<ul class=\"check-list\">\n<li><a href=\"https://api.marketplacer.com/docs/webhooks/webhooksoverview/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Webhooks overview</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"https://api.marketplacer.com/docs/webhooks/webhooksgettingstarted/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Getting Started with Webhooks</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"https://api.marketplacer.com/docs/webhooks/eventmatrix/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Event Matrix</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"https://api.marketplacer.com/docs/webhooks/webhookretries/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Webhook retry policy</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"https://api.marketplacer.com/docs/webhooks/deduplication/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Webhook deduplication</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"https://api.marketplacer.com/docs/webhooks/highvolumewebhooks/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">High-volume Webhooks</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"https://api.marketplacer.com/docs/webhooks/securingwebhooks/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Securing Webhooks</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"https://api.marketplacer.com/docs/webhooks/errorsfaults/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Errors and faults</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"https://api.marketplacer.com/docs/operator-api/examples/utility/howto_managewebhooks/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Manage Webhooks through the Operator API</a></li>\n</ul>\n"},"related":[["integration-architecture","Integration Architecture"],["apis","APIs"],["source-of-truth-planning","Source-of-Truth Planning"],["integration-troubleshooting","Integration Troubleshooting"],["mconnect","MConnect"]]},"source-of-truth-planning":{"summary":"Decide which system owns every marketplace object and field, document update and overwrite rules, prevent circular synchronisation and give Operations a clear process for resolving conflicting data.","audience":["Marketplace operations","Product and catalogue","Technology and integrations","Finance","Seller management"],"sections":{"Understand Source of Truth":"<p>A source of truth is the system or controlled record with authority over a particular value. When systems disagree, it determines which value wins, where correction occurs, which copies update and who owns the issue.</p>\n<div class=\"structure-diagram\"><code>Seller Shopify owns stock\n      ↓\nMConnect copies stock to Marketplacer\n      ↓\nStorefront displays availability</code></div>\n\n<p>A marketplace can have many sources of truth. It should not have two uncontrolled sources for the same field.</p>\n","Distinguish Source of Truth from System of Record":"<p>The source of truth owns a value or decision. The system of record retains the official transactional or operational record. A display layer presents information, while a processing system performs a specialised action.</p>\n<p>For example, the Seller platform can own stock, Marketplacer can be the system of record for the marketplace Order and remittance, the storefront can display the customer Order and the payment provider can own payment status.</p>\n","Assign Ownership at Object and Field Level":"<p>Object ownership can be too broad for products assembled from several systems.</p>\n<div class=\"data-table-wrap\"><table class=\"data-table\">\n<thead>\n<tr>\n  <th>Product field</th>\n  <th>Example source of truth</th>\n</tr>\n</thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n  <td>Source title and SKU</td>\n  <td>Seller platform</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n  <td>Marketplace Category</td>\n  <td>Marketplacer</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n  <td>Price and stock</td>\n  <td>Seller platform or approved pricing system</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n  <td>Shipping Profile</td>\n  <td>Marketplacer</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n  <td>Golden Record identity</td>\n  <td>Marketplacer CPD</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div>\n<p>Use object-level ownership for a complete Refund Request, payment transaction or payout. Use field-level ownership for products, Sellers and regional data.</p>\n","Start with Business Decisions":"<p>Before selecting API fields, decide who is responsible, where they maintain information, who approves changes, what customers see, what happens when data is missing and whether an integration can overwrite it.</p>\n<p>A Seller can provide the initial title while Marketplacer becomes the ongoing marketplace title source after enrichment, or the Seller source can remain authoritative. Both models work when the transition is explicit.</p>\n","Build a Source-of-Truth Register":"<p>The register should include object, field, source, initial source, ongoing source, destinations, direction, trigger, frequency, transformation, overwrite behaviour, manual-edit policy, owners, failure process and reconciliation.</p>\n<p>Treat this register as part of the architecture and operating model, not temporary onboarding notes.</p>\n","Define Write, Read and Display Responsibilities":"<p>For each system, record whether it can create, update, read, display, delete or approve an object. A system that reads or displays a field does not automatically own it.</p>\n<p>This prevents a customer storefront, search index or reporting warehouse from becoming an accidental write source.</p>\n","Plan Product and Catalogue Ownership":"<p>Products commonly flow from Seller source to Marketplacer Mapping and validation, optional Golden Records and then the storefront.</p>\n<p>Confirm ownership of title, description, Category, Brand, Option Types, images, publication, marketplace enrichment and Golden Record content.</p>\n<p>The Seller source Category is input to Mapping. Marketplacer owns the approved marketplace Category after Mapping.</p>\n","Plan MConnect Field Ownership":"<p>MConnect can use all supported fields during initial creation and only configured fields for ongoing updates.</p>\n<p>Build a field matrix covering title, description, images, price, Sale price, stock, SKU, barcode, Category and Shipping Profile. Manual Marketplacer edits to a synchronised field may be overwritten.</p>\n<p>Do not enable missing-source controls that assume every product belongs to Shopify when the Seller account also contains manual, API or feed-managed products.</p>\n","Plan Golden Record and CPD Ownership":"<p>Golden Records can own shared product identity, title, description, Brand, Category, images and specifications. Seller offers continue to own Seller identity, price, stock, SKU, shipping and fulfilment.</p>\n<p>Define the Golden Record source Advert, whether Seller updates propagate, fallback behaviour, source-change approval and each Seller's backfill policy: Never, Only If Missing or Always.</p>\n<p>Prevent circular flow between Seller source, Seller Advert, Golden Record and backfill.</p>\n","Plan Storefront Enrichment":"<p>Storefront enrichment can be display-only, stored only in the ecommerce platform or written back through an approved integration.</p>\n<p>Define which fields are protected from future Marketplacer updates, whether enrichment resets, and whether any write-back is allowed. Do not create automatic write-back merely because the storefront supports editing.</p>\n","Plan Price and Sale-Price Ownership":"<p>Confirm source price, marketplace selling price, Sale price, RRP, wholesale price, tax inclusion, currency, regional pricing and effective dates.</p>\n<p>A Sale price is Variant pricing state. A Promotion is a separate customer benefit with eligibility and funding treatment. Record them separately.</p>\n<p>Manual changes to Seller-source price should normally be prohibited in Marketplacer unless price sync has deliberately been disabled.</p>\n","Plan Stock and Availability Ownership":"<p>Choose one operational stock source, such as Seller ecommerce, ERP, POS, warehouse, Seller Portal or Seller API. Document stock buffer, location, cadence, Order reduction, infinite stock and reconciliation.</p>\n<p>Positive stock does not guarantee customer availability. Mapping, Product Vetting, Catalog Rules, publication and Seller status also matter.</p>\n","Plan Promotions and Regional Data":"<p>For Promotions, identify who owns campaign configuration, customer eligibility, display, discount calculation, Seller-funded share, Operator-funded share, Order adjustment and reporting.</p>\n<p>For regional pricing or translated content, define each structured field, owner, locale selection and fallback. A storefront can choose the correct locale field without creating separate Golden Records for identical products.</p>\n","Plan Order and Payment Ownership":"<p>Recommended ownership separates checkout and customer-facing Order in the ecommerce platform, payment status in the payment provider, marketplace Order and Seller Invoices in Marketplacer and Seller-platform Order in the fulfilment system.</p>\n<p>Retain storefront Order, payment transaction, Marketplacer Order, Seller Invoice and Seller-platform Order IDs together.</p>\n","Plan Fulfilment Ownership":"<p>Dispatch can begin in the Seller Portal, Seller ecommerce platform through MConnect or a custom Seller API integration.</p>\n<p>Define ownership of quantity, Carrier, tracking, Shipment date, partial and split Shipment, collection and delivery confirmation. The storefront may display fulfilment but should not independently rewrite Seller Shipments without an approved flow.</p>\n","Plan Cancellation, Return and Refund Ownership":"<p>Separate customer request intake, Marketplacer Refund Request, Seller decision, return movement, Invoice Amendment, payment refund, Seller recovery and accounting.</p>\n<p>A refund is fully reconciled only when the Marketplacer workflow, customer payment refund and Seller financial adjustment agree.</p>\n","Plan Remittance and Payout Ownership":"<p>Marketplacer can own commission, fees, adjustments, remittance eligibility and amount due. The payout provider or bank owns actual transfer status, and Finance owns accounting reconciliation.</p>\n<p>Retain Remittance Advice ID, payout transaction ID, transfer status and date. Do not mark a Seller paid merely because a Remittance Advice exists.</p>\n","Use Marketplacer IDs and External IDs":"<p>Use Marketplacer GraphQL IDs for Marketplacer objects and External IDs for durable third-party correlation.</p>\n<p>External IDs can connect storefront Orders, payment references, Seller Orders and ERP records to Marketplacer. They do not replace Marketplacer IDs and should use standard naming conventions.</p>\n","Choose Between Metadata, Custom Fields and Native Fields":"<div class=\"data-table-wrap\"><table class=\"data-table\">\n<thead>\n<tr>\n  <th>Requirement</th>\n  <th>Use</th>\n</tr>\n</thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n  <td>Platform behaviour exists</td>\n  <td>Native field</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n  <td>Third-party identifier</td>\n  <td>External ID</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n  <td>Integration-only context</td>\n  <td>Metadata</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n  <td>Approved structured additional attribute</td>\n  <td>Custom field</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div>\n<p>Metadata is not a replacement for a searchable External ID or a native field. Do not store prohibited personal or regulated information in custom fields or metadata.</p>\n","Define Update Direction and Timing":"<p>Document one-way, outward or controlled two-way flow, trigger and acceptable latency for every field.</p>\n<p>Two-way synchronisation requires field or state ownership, loop prevention, stable identifiers, conflict rules, timestamps and duplicate handling. Define latency expectations for content, price, stock, Orders, Shipments, refunds and remittance.</p>\n","Separate Initial Creation from Ongoing Updates":"<p>The system that supplies a value during record creation may not remain the ongoing owner.</p>\n<p>Example: Shopify creates title, price and stock; Marketplacer Mapping owns Category; Operator enrichment becomes the description source; Shopify remains the ongoing price and stock source.</p>\n<p>Record both initial and ongoing rules.</p>\n","Control Manual Edits":"<p>Classify manual edits as durable, temporary or prohibited.</p>\n<p>Before changing a connected field, check source of truth, ongoing sync, overwrite risk, downstream flow, approval and validation. Prefer correcting the source and letting the integration propagate the change.</p>\n","Define Overwrite and Conflict Rules":"<p>Choose an explicit rule: always overwrite, only if missing, never overwrite, most recent approved update or manual review.</p>\n<p>Use manual review for duplicate barcodes, conflicting tax, contractual pricing or conflicting fulfilment quantities. Do not default to last update wins merely because it is simple.</p>\n","Prevent Circular Synchronisation":"<p>Prevent loops with one-way ownership, source markers, External IDs, event-origin metadata, version checks, no-op comparisons and write suppression for self-generated changes.</p>\n<p>If the incoming value already equals the destination value, avoid another write and unnecessary Webhook activity.</p>\n","Manage Source Changes and Fallbacks":"<p>When a Seller changes platform or a Golden Record source changes, inventory affected fields, stop the old write path, preserve identifiers, migrate and reconcile data, enable the new path, monitor and retire old credentials.</p>\n<p>If Golden Record fallback assigns a new source, review its content quality because future updates can overwrite the Golden Record.</p>\n","Govern Deletion and Deactivation":"<p>A source product disappearing can mean intentional removal, tag change, source outage or incomplete feed. Prefer controlled zero-stock or inactive states before irreversible deletion where appropriate.</p>\n<p>Seller offboarding must cover open Orders, returns, product publication, Golden Record source reassignment, remittance and credential revocation.</p>\n","Monitor Data Lineage and Reconcile Systems":"<p>Retain source ID and timestamp, integration name and event, transformation, destination ID and timestamp and user or service identity.</p>\n<p>Reconcile stock, price, Orders and Shipments frequently; refunds and remittance regularly; product content and taxonomy periodically. A successful job does not prove every record is aligned.</p>\n","Apply Change Control":"<p>Treat changes to MConnect fields, Product source, stock source, Golden propagation, backfill, storefront write-back, Order creation, payments, payouts and External ID conventions as architecture changes.</p>\n<p>Document old and new source, affected fields, migration, overwrite behaviour, test, rollback, owners, deployment and reconciliation. Update the register and runbooks after release.</p>\n","Troubleshoot Source-of-Truth Conflicts":"<h3>Manual change disappeared</h3>\n<p>Check MConnect sync, Golden backfill, source propagation, API jobs and Activity Logs.</p>\n<h3>Marketplacer and storefront disagree</h3>\n<p>Check last Marketplacer update, outbound connector or Webhook, destination processing, index, cache and storefront-owned enrichment.</p>\n<h3>Stock keeps changing back</h3>\n<p>Check active source, buffer, location, another integration, Order reduction and source replenishment.</p>\n<h3>Refund systems disagree</h3>\n<p>Compare Refund Request, Invoice Amendment, payment refund, remittance and External IDs.</p>\n","Test Source-of-Truth Rules End to End":"<p>Test initial product creation, later updates, protected Marketplacer fields, MConnect source removal, Golden source change and fallback, each backfill policy, storefront enrichment, price and stock updates, Order correlation, fulfilment sequencing, refund reconciliation and source migration with rollback.</p>\n","Operator Readiness Checklist":"<ul class=\"check-list\">\n<li>source of truth, system of record and display roles are distinguished</li>\n<li>critical objects have object or field-level ownership</li>\n<li>initial and ongoing ownership are documented separately</li>\n<li>MConnect, Golden Records and storefront enrichment follow the ownership model</li>\n<li>price, stock, Promotions, Orders, payments, fulfilment, refunds, remittance and payouts have clear authorities</li>\n<li>IDs, External IDs, metadata and custom fields are used deliberately</li>\n<li>overwrite, conflict, loop-prevention, deletion and fallback rules are explicit</li>\n<li>manual edits and source transitions follow change control</li>\n<li>lineage and reconciliation are owned and tested</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>Related Marketplacer articles</h3>\n<ul class=\"check-list\">\n<li><a href=\"https://support.marketplacer.com/hc/en-us/articles/21419183202957-Configure-product-sync-rules\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Configure product sync rules</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"https://support.marketplacer.com/hc/en-us/articles/7923331702669-Shopify-Integration-for-sellers-Settings-and-Best-Practices\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Shopify settings and best practices</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"https://support.marketplacer.com/hc/en-us/articles/37154546531341-Understanding-the-source-for-a-Golden-Record\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Understanding the source for a Golden Record</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"https://support.marketplacer.com/hc/en-us/articles/24734837065613-Backfill-and-Autopublish\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Backfill and Autopublish</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"https://api.marketplacer.com/docs/operator-api/examples/orders/howto_order/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Creating Orders</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"https://api.marketplacer.com/docs/operator-api/examples/utility/howto_add_externalids/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">External IDs</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"https://api.marketplacer.com/docs/operator-api/examples/utility/howto_metadata/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Metadata</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"https://api.marketplacer.com/docs/operator-api/examples/utility/howto_customfields/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Custom fields</a></li>\n</ul>\n"},"related":[["integration-architecture","Integration Architecture"],["apis","APIs"],["webhooks","Webhooks"],["mconnect","MConnect"],["golden-records","Golden Records"]]},"integration-troubleshooting":{"summary":"Investigate integration issues methodically across source systems, Marketplacer, connectors, APIs, Webhooks and destination platforms, recover failed records safely and escalate with complete evidence.","audience":["Marketplace operations","Technology and integrations","Ecommerce","Customer service","Finance"],"sections":{"Understand Integration Troubleshooting":"<p>Integration troubleshooting determines what failed, where, when, which records were affected, whether systems disagree, whether an automated retry remains active, whether manual recovery is safe and which team owns the next action.</p>\n<div class=\"callout note\">\n<p>Do not begin by retrying. Find the last confirmed successful point in the data flow.</p>\n</div>\n<p>A report that a product is missing can originate in source selection, import, Mapping, validation, Product Vetting, publication, stock, outbound integration, indexing or merchandising.</p>\n","Distinguish Delay, Data Discrepancy and Failure":"<p>An expected delay remains within the approved processing window. A data discrepancy means source and destination differ after that window. A processing failure has a recorded error. A silent business failure occurs when the technical request succeeded but downstream processing did not.</p>\n<p>A Webhook Sent status or HTTP <code>200</code> does not prove the destination completed the action.</p>\n","Classify Impact and Urgency":"<p>Critical examples include customers charged without Orders, duplicate Orders, widespread incorrect price or stock, refunds not paid and materially incorrect payouts.</p>\n<p>High impact can include one Seller missing Orders, widespread fulfilment failure or disabled synchronisation. Moderate impact can be an individual product or Shipment issue.</p>\n<p>State impact precisely, including environment, Seller, flow, record count and start time.</p>\n","Stabilise the Marketplace Before Investigation":"<p>Contain unsafe activity by pausing Product or Invoice sync, disabling a Webhook, stopping an API worker, suspending a Promotion, removing affected products from sale or stopping automated payouts.</p>\n<p>Capture screenshots, settings, logs, payloads, statuses and last known successful record before changing configuration. Separate containment from permanent repair.</p>\n","Start with One Affected Record":"<p>Choose one representative Product, Variant, Invoice, Order, Shipment, Refund Request or Remittance Advice with stable identifiers and a clear expected result.</p>\n<p>Use that record to locate the failing boundary, then identify the complete affected population after the cause is known.</p>\n","Build an End-to-End Timeline":"<p>Build a chronological table using source update, connector job, API request, Marketplacer creation, Webhook generation, destination processing and business outcome timestamps.</p>\n<p>Record timezone and UTC where available. A display-time-zone difference can look like an integration delay.</p>\n","Trace the Record Across Every System":"<p>Use a left-to-right sequence: source, integration, Marketplacer, outbound integration, destination and business outcome.</p>\n<p>Confirm the source record, trigger, transformation, request, response, Marketplacer object and status, destination record, indexing and final customer, Seller or Finance result.</p>\n","Preserve Identifiers and Evidence":"<p>Retain source Product and Variant IDs, Marketplacer Advert and Variant IDs, Golden IDs, storefront IDs, barcodes and SKUs.</p>\n<p>For transactions, retain storefront Order, payment, Marketplacer Order, Seller Invoice, Line Item, Seller-platform Order, Shipment, Refund Request and payout IDs.</p>\n<p>Redact API keys, passwords, HMAC secrets, payment credentials and unnecessary personal data.</p>\n","Confirm the Expected Integration Behaviour":"<p>Review architecture, source-of-truth register, connector support, field Mapping, cadence, publication rules, Product Vetting, API scopes, Webhook Event Matrix, retries and financial policies.</p>\n<p>Many reported defects are expectation gaps, such as a synchronised description overwriting a manual edit, a no-stock import rule excluding products or a Marketplacer refund not automatically moving customer cash.</p>\n","Identify the Failing Boundary":"<p>Ask whether the source created correct data, the integration read and transformed it, the destination accepted it and the next system processed it.</p>\n<p>Source errors belong to the source. Transformation errors belong to the connector or middleware. A valid Marketplacer record with a missing storefront result points downstream. Do not assign ownership only from where the symptom was noticed.</p>\n","Use Operator Portal Investigation Tools":"<p>Use <strong>Reporting &gt; MConnect Report</strong>, External IDs, Problem Reports, Activity Logs and the actual Product, Variant, Order, Invoice, Shipment, Refund Request or Remittance Advice pages.</p>\n<p>Problem Reports are evidence, not automatic proof that Marketplacer is the root cause. Combine Portal evidence with integration and destination logs.</p>\n","Troubleshoot Product and Catalogue Flows":"<p>Trace Seller source, import, Mapping, validation, Product Vetting, publication and storefront.</p>\n<p>If the product never entered Marketplacer, check source status, tags, exclusions, Product source, stock requirement, credentials and imports. If it exists but is invalid, check Brand, Category, Prototype, Options, mandatory fields, images, Shipping Profile and Catalog Rules.</p>\n<p>If Marketplacer is correct but the storefront is missing it, check product-state filters, Webhook or outbound query, transformation, index, cache and merchandising.</p>\n","Troubleshoot Price and Stock":"<p>For price, compare source, connector payload, Marketplacer Variant, Sale price, Promotion, storefront, checkout and Line Item. Check tax, currency, rounding, effective dates and regional logic.</p>\n<p>For stock, compare source location, buffer, Marketplacer count, Orders and storefront. Check sync cadence, infinite stock, missing-source handling, tags, disabled integration and competing writers.</p>\n<p>Correct the authoritative source rather than relying on an emergency manual edit that the next sync will overwrite.</p>\n","Troubleshoot Order Creation":"<p>Trace payment, integration request, Marketplacer Order, Seller Invoices and Seller systems.</p>\n<p>When payment exists but no Order is visible, inspect <code>orderCreate</code>, GraphQL and mutation errors, Variant IDs, stock, quantity, money and tax inputs, Promotion adjustment, scopes, timeout, retry queue and External ID search.</p>\n<p>If Marketplacer created the Order but the caller timed out, search before retrying.</p>\n","Troubleshoot Seller Invoice Delivery":"<p>Confirm the Seller Invoice, status, notification method, MConnect Invoice sync, start date, connected-service ID, integration status and Seller-platform Order.</p>\n<p>Use individual Invoice sync only after searching the Seller platform and confirming the Order does not already exist. Historical Invoices may be outside the configured sync boundary.</p>\n","Troubleshoot Fulfilment and Tracking":"<p>Confirm source fulfilment, quantities, Carrier, tracking, connector support, MConnect status, Marketplacer Shipment, Shipment Webhook and storefront tracking.</p>\n<p>Use the MConnect fulfilment-status check when the connected Order exists but the Invoice remains Paid. For partial fulfilment, compare quantities and remaining balance rather than treating the whole Invoice as Sent.</p>\n","Troubleshoot Cancellations, Returns and Refunds":"<p>Compare customer request, Marketplacer Refund Request, Seller action, Invoice Amendment, payment-provider refund and Seller remittance.</p>\n<p>A Marketplacer Refunded status does not prove customer cash moved. A payment-only refund can leave Seller remittance wrong. Before retrying a refund, search both Marketplacer and the payment provider.</p>\n","Troubleshoot Remittance and Payouts":"<p>Separate eligibility, Remittance Advice, approval, payout-provider transaction, bank transfer and Seller receipt.</p>\n<p>When amount differs, compare gross Line Items, commission, postage, merchant fees, tax, Promotion funding, cancellations, refunds and other adjustments.</p>\n<p>Before recreating a payout, confirm the original is not pending or completed and obtain Finance approval.</p>\n","Troubleshoot MConnect":"<p>Use Settings, Imports, Items, Invoices, raw data, Audit Logs, MConnect Report, Seller source and Marketplacer records.</p>\n<p>For one product, confirm source status, tags, exclusions, fields to sync and Item error, then correct the source and use individual import.</p>\n<p>If Product or Invoice sync is disabled, review the fatal error, credentials and source application, correct the cause, test one record and reconcile the disabled period.</p>\n","Troubleshoot APIs":"<p>Inspect HTTP status, headers, top-level GraphQL errors, <code>extensions.code</code>, mutation errors, returned object and status.</p>\n<p>Check endpoint, environment, authentication, scope, variables, IDs, stock, business state, pagination and rate limits.</p>\n<p>For an uncertain mutation outcome, query by External ID and inspect Webhooks and destination records before retrying.</p>\n","Troubleshoot Webhooks":"<p>Confirm the Marketplacer event occurred, a Webhook Event was generated, delivery was attempted, the endpoint response, consumer processing and destination update.</p>\n<p>No event can indicate wrong object, Event Name or Event Matrix assumption. Rejected or Failed can indicate timeout, <code>429</code>, <code>5xx</code>, authentication, DNS, TLS or receiver capacity. Sent with no destination change points to the consumer after acceptance.</p>\n","Handle Timeouts and Uncertain Outcomes":"<p>A timeout proves the response was not received, not that the mutation failed.</p>\n<p>Stop blind retry, retain the payload, search by External ID, query the expected record, review Webhooks and destination records, then retry only if no original record exists. Apply this to Orders, Shipments, refunds, payouts and Seller-system Order creation.</p>\n","Retry Safely":"<p>Retry temporary timeout, network, <code>429</code>, <code>503</code> and platform-availability conditions. Correct invalid payload, ID, credential, scope or business state first.</p>\n<p>Safe retries require a stable External ID, duplicate check, maximum attempts, backoff, retry logging, one processing owner and an exception queue.</p>\n","Investigate Duplicate Records":"<p>Duplicates can arise from timeout retries, two workers, Webhook redelivery, manual recovery during automated retry, MConnect reconnection or several ingestion methods controlling the same record.</p>\n<p>Compare External IDs, source IDs, payment, Seller, Product, quantities, timestamps and destination IDs. Before removing a duplicate, determine which record has the valid payment, Seller fulfilment, refund and remittance history.</p>\n","Recover Data Without Hiding the Root Cause":"<p>Good recovery corrects the source, runs a controlled single-record import and validates every destination. A manual destination edit while the source remains active can hide the issue temporarily and be overwritten.</p>\n<p>Record affected object, hypothesis, manual action, user, time, expected automation, validation and follow-up reconciliation.</p>\n","Reconcile After Recovery":"<p>For Products, confirm source, Marketplacer Product and Variant, publication, stock and storefront. For Orders, confirm payment, storefront Order, Marketplacer Order, Seller Invoices, Seller Orders and fulfilment. For refunds and payouts, confirm every workflow and financial record.</p>\n<p>After solving the sample record, identify the full incident period and classify all records as complete, missing, duplicate or incorrect.</p>\n","Decide Whether the Issue Belongs to Marketplacer":"<p>Escalate when a valid request behaves contrary to current documentation, a supported event is missing, Marketplacer records disagree internally, the service is unavailable or documented recovery does not work.</p>\n<p>Continue internal or partner investigation for source-data errors, credentials, scopes, invalid payloads, endpoint errors, Mapping, unsupported assumptions or source-of-truth conflicts.</p>\n<p>Joint ownership is common. Marketplacer can generate a Webhook correctly while the Operator endpoint returns <code>500</code>.</p>\n","Escalate to Marketplacer Support":"<p>Include marketplace, environment, impact, Seller, object type, record and External IDs, timestamps and timezone, exact steps, expected and actual behaviour, screenshots, redacted request and response evidence, relevant settings, completed checks and workaround.</p>\n<p>Use a subject that names the flow and impact. Do not submit only &quot;Orders are broken&quot;.</p>\n","Complete Root-Cause Analysis":"<p>Classify root cause as source data, configuration, access, unsupported assumption, code defect, platform defect, credential expiry, retry design, capacity, source-of-truth conflict, manual process or missing monitoring.</p>\n<p>Identify why the issue reached customers, then assign immediate fix, permanent fix, monitoring, testing, documentation and ownership actions.</p>\n","Maintain Integration Runbooks":"<p>Maintain runbooks for missing Products, stale price and stock, overwrites, missing or duplicate Orders, Seller Invoice delivery, Shipments, Webhooks, API authentication, disabled sync, refund mismatch, payout mismatch and Sandbox refresh.</p>\n<p>Each runbook should state trigger, impact, containment, investigation, recovery, duplicate protection, validation, escalation, evidence and closure criteria.</p>\n","Test Failure and Recovery Scenarios":"<p>Test Product validation and publication failures, stale price and stock, payment success with Order failure, timeout after creation, duplicate retry, missing Seller Invoice, partial fulfilment, refund mismatches, MConnect credential failure, API errors and rate limits, Webhook timeout and requeue, and cross-environment mistakes.</p>\n","Operator Readiness Checklist":"<ul class=\"check-list\">\n<li>every integration has business, technical and operational owners</li>\n<li>architecture, source-of-truth rules, IDs and latency targets are documented</li>\n<li>unsafe flows can be paused and evidence preserved</li>\n<li>teams can trace one record end to end</li>\n<li>MConnect, API and Webhook investigation tools and recovery actions are understood</li>\n<li>uncertain outcomes require lookup before retry</li>\n<li>Orders, refunds and payouts are duplicate-safe</li>\n<li>Product, Order, fulfilment, refund and Finance reconciliation are scheduled</li>\n<li>Support escalation includes complete evidence</li>\n<li>significant incidents require root-cause analysis and corrective action</li>\n<li>runbooks and failure-recovery tests are current</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>Related Marketplacer articles</h3>\n<ul class=\"check-list\">\n<li><a href=\"https://support.marketplacer.com/hc/en-us/articles/360012519092-MConnect-Marketplacer-Integrations\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">MConnect</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"https://support.marketplacer.com/hc/en-us/articles/10494375967501-Single-product-import-in-MConnect\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Single Product import</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"https://support.marketplacer.com/hc/en-us/articles/15500690036237-Single-invoice-sync-and-fulfilment-status-check-in-MConnect\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Single Invoice sync and fulfilment check</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"https://support.marketplacer.com/hc/en-us/articles/6646120206733-Integration-error-detection-in-MConnect\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Integration error detection</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"https://api.marketplacer.com/docs/operator-api/overview/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Operator API overview</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"https://api.marketplacer.com/docs/webhooks/errorsfaults/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Webhook errors and faults</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"https://api.marketplacer.com/docs/webhooks/webhooksoverview/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Webhooks overview</a></li>\n</ul>\n"},"related":[["integration-architecture","Integration Architecture"],["apis","APIs"],["webhooks","Webhooks"],["source-of-truth-planning","Source-of-Truth Planning"],["mconnect","MConnect"]]}};
